WEBVTT

1
00:00.840 --> 00:04.650
- Welcome back to Understanding
Quantum Information and Computation.

2
00:04.650 --> 00:09.750
My name is John Watrous and I'm the technical director
for IBM Quantum Education.

3
00:09.750 --> 00:15.900
This is the third lesson of the series. In the first two lessons, we talked about the basics
of quantum information.

4
00:15.900 --> 00:20.760
First for single systems in isolation and then for multiple systems.

5
00:20.760 --> 00:28.800
We also discussed standard
basis measurements and unitary operations in both the single and
multiple system settings.

6
00:28.800 --> 00:35.280
In this lesson, we'll introduce
the quantum circuit model, which gives us a standard way to describe quantum computations,

7
00:35.280 --> 00:43.260
and we can also use quantum circuits to describe quantum protocols and other sorts of interactions involving multiple quantum devices.

8
00:43.260 --> 00:49.320
In addition to quantum circuits, we'll also discuss some
important mathematical concepts connected with quantum information,

9
00:49.320 --> 00:56.550
and we'll use them to observe
a few fundamental limitations on quantum information and what we can do with quantum circuits.

10
00:56.550 --> 01:03.865
That'll set us up well for
the lesson following this one where we'll see a few
very important examples and that will conclude the
first unit of the series

11
01:03.865 --> 01:07.680
on the basics of quantum information.

12
01:07.680 --> 01:14.820
Here's an overview of the lesson. We'll start with the quantum circuit model and we'll see how it works.

13
01:14.820 --> 01:21.150
Then we'll talk about the
critically important notion of an inner product, as well as orthonormality and projections,

14
01:21.150 --> 01:29.850
which are connected with inner products. We didn't discuss these things
in the first two lessons, because we really didn't
need to, but now we do.

15
01:29.850 --> 01:34.320
Inner products provide us
with a mathematical tool that we simply could not do without.

16
01:34.320 --> 01:40.230
We just would not get far in understanding quantum information and
computation without inner products.

17
01:40.230 --> 01:46.080
And in the third part of the lesson, we'll take a look at a
few important limitations of quantum information.

18
01:46.080 --> 01:53.550
Ultimately, what we want to do is to explore interesting
things that we can do with quantum information, but in order to do this effectively,

19
01:53.550 --> 01:57.120
we need to be aware of some
things that we can't do.

20
01:57.120 --> 02:03.060
In particular, we'll discuss
the notion of a global phase and why global phases are irrelevant.

21
02:03.060 --> 02:10.500
We'll see a statement of
the no-cloning theorem, which tells us that quantum states can't be copied in general, and we'll see that two quantum states

22
02:10.500 --> 02:18.960
can't be perfectly
discriminated from one another unless they're orthogonal, which is a fundamental
limitation to be aware of.

23
02:18.960 --> 02:24.990
The first topic for the lesson
is the quantum circuit model, which is a model of computation
that provides us with a way

24
02:24.990 --> 02:28.740
to describe quantum computations.

25
02:28.740 --> 02:36.490
The quantum circuit model is
based on a more general notion in computer science of a circuit, and you can define many
different models of computation

26
02:36.490 --> 02:40.170
based on this general notion.

27
02:40.170 --> 02:47.370
The basic idea is that a
circuit is composed of wires which carry information, and gates, which represent operations

28
02:47.370 --> 02:51.570
that are applied to the
information carried by the wires.

29
02:51.570 --> 02:57.900
The term circuit is actually
kind of a strange name to use for this sort of a model
because the word circuit

30
02:57.900 --> 03:01.590
usually refers to a
circular path of some sort.

31
03:01.590 --> 03:07.680
But when we talk about circuits
as models of computation, we're usually talking
about acyclic circuits

32
03:07.680 --> 03:11.160
where circular paths are not allowed.

33
03:11.160 --> 03:19.650
To be more precise, for the
purposes of this series, we're going to demand that
information always flows from left to right in any circuit.

34
03:19.650 --> 03:29.040
So if you prefer, you
can think about circuits as describing sequences of operations where time goes from left to right.

35
03:29.040 --> 03:35.130
Here's an example of a Boolean circuit where the wires carry binary
values, either zero or one,

36
03:35.130 --> 03:39.030
and the gates represent
Boolean logic operations.

37
03:39.030 --> 03:45.210
The wires are represented by lines, and here we have two input
bits labeled X and Y,

38
03:45.210 --> 03:51.960
and if we want to know
what the circuit does on a particular choice of inputs, we propagate the values on
the wires from left to right,

39
03:51.960 --> 03:57.960
depending on the actions
that the gates have on the values that are
carried by the wires.

40
03:57.960 --> 04:07.770
So for instance, we can
take a look at what happens when we start out with the top input wire set to the value one and the bottom input wire
set to the value zero.

41
04:07.770 --> 04:15.060
These two input wires lead
into these two dots right here, which represent fan-out operations, which means that the value is copied

42
04:15.060 --> 04:18.870
so that it can be carried
forward along multiple wires.

43
04:18.870 --> 04:25.710
So if we do this, then these
two wires take the value one, which is the same as this one, and these two wires take the value zero,

44
04:25.710 --> 04:29.520
which is the same as this one.

45
04:29.520 --> 04:36.180
Here we have a NOT gate which
is indicated by the symbol for logical negation, so the
value that comes out is a zero,

46
04:36.180 --> 04:46.380
which is the logical negation of one. And similarly, the value
that comes out of this gate is a one which is the
logical negation of zero.

47
04:46.380 --> 04:53.010
These two gates are AND gates,
this gate is an OR gate, and if we continue on
and propagate the values

